In addition, the project also aimed to probe the reception of English medium education among students at MUST. In particular, it was hoped that the qualitative interviews which were
                part of the data collection would help shed light on what has been called ‘the linguistic worlds’ of Chinese students coming from rapidly‐changing multilingual backgrounds (Bolton

               ; 
               ).

The research used an eclectic sociolinguistic approach with various methods being utilized for data collection. The primary research method was a sociolinguistic questionnaire which
                    was given to a sample universe consisting of teaching staff and undergraduate students. This questionnaire was adapted from a survey designed by Bacon‐Shone et al. (
                  ), which was utilized in amended form by Bolton and Kuteeva (
                  ), with the latter assessing the use of English for
                    academic purposes at Stockholm University. This questionnaire was first translated into Chinese in order to create a bilingual version of the questionnaire. The bilingual version
                    allowed all the participants to optimize their chances for fully understanding the text of each question.

The beliefs and attitudes about English as well as the exposure to English on the MUST campus do appear to impact the personal lives of Chinese university learners and teaching staff, especially in the way they access content on the Internet, and socialize with their friends. Also noteworthy is that 55 per cent of students in this study reported to speak and/or read English within two days of the survey, and the most surprising result of this study is students and lecturers claiming to use English when socializing with their friends, co‐workers, classmates, and online (virtual) communities (cf. Tables
and
). In fact 27.7 per cent of students reportedly last used English for socializing, with the same amount of students claiming to use English for their studies in their leisure time. The results of the extra‐curricular use of English also correspond loosely to the amount of English students reportedly are exposed to in their respective faculties, with hospitality and tourism as well as management and administration students reportedly using English the most in their spare time.

This study is part of a large‐scale sociolinguistic project to evaluate the impact and actual (reported) use of English on Chinese university campuses, in terms of the values that
                    learners and other English‐medium instruction stakeholders have about English as well as the realities that all stakeholders confront in these educational contexts. This present
                    study predicts that future research requires ethnographic studies to determine the use of English by Chinese students in terms of identity (re)construction in interaction, as well
                    as the kind of social information which might be indexed (Silverstein 
                  ; 
                  ) by the use of English (such as the
                    study of Wu 
                  ). Future studies may also probe the actual language use of teachers and students in their educational settings, with the view to
                    establishing the amount of code‐switching and/or actual English use within academic discourse settings on Chinese university campuses.
